tions in her discipline: Why do art historians write in the first place? What kinds of psychic exchanges occur between art objects and those who write about them? What institutional and personal needs does art history serve? What is lost in historical writing about art? The Melancholy Art looks at how melancholy suffuses the work of some of the twentieth century's most powerful and poetic writers on the history of art, including Alois Riegl, Franz Wickhoff, Adrian Stokes, Michael Baxandall, Meyer Schapiro, and Jacques Derrida. A disarmingly personal meditation by one of our most distinguished art historians, this book explains why to write about art is to share in a kind of intertwined pleasure and loss that is the very essence of melancholy.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArt - Historiography. 0aArtxHistoriography. 0aMelancholy. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAby Warburg.  aAestheticism.  aAesthetics.  aAllegory.  aAlois Riegl.  aAnachronism.  aAnalytic confidence.  aAncient art.  aAphorism.  aArt criticism.  aArt history.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aArtistic merit.  aBen Nicholson.  aBernard Berenson.  aBernard Bosanquet (philosopher).  aBeyond the Pleasure Principle.  aCaspar David Friedrich.  aChristopher Bollas.  aClassicism.  aConnoisseur.  aConsciousness.  aContemporary art.  aCriticism.  aCritique of Judgment.  aDeath drive.  aDeconstruction.  aErnst Gombrich.  aErwin Panofsky.  aExplanation.  aFra Angelico.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aFritz Saxl.  aGarry Wills.  aGeorg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel.  aGeorge Steiner.  aGiovanni Morelli.  aHannah Arendt.  aHans Ulrich Gumbrecht.  aHayden White.  aIconography.  aIllusionism (art).  aIsabella Stewart Gar